TY  - JOUR
AU  - Jouini, Elyès
AU  - Napp, Clotilde
AU  - Viossat, Yannick
T1  - Evolutionary Beliefs and Financial Markets*
PY  - 2013
Y1  - 2013/04/01
DO  - 10.1093/rof/rfs004
JO  - Review of Finance
JA  - Rev Financ
VL  - 17
IS  - 2
SP  - 727
EP  - 766
SN  - 1572-3097
AB  - Why do investors keep different opinions even though they learn from their own failures and successes? Why do investors keep different opinions even though they observe each other and learn from their relative failures and successes? We analyze beliefs dynamics when beliefs result from a very general learning process that favors beliefs leading to higher absolute or relative utility levels. We show that such a process converges to the Nash equilibrium in a game of strategic belief choices. The asymptotic beliefs are subjective and heterogeneous across the agents. Optimism (respectively overconfidence) as well as pessimism (respectively doubt) emerge from the learning process. Furthermore, we obtain a positive correlation between pessimism (respectively doubt) and risk tolerance. Under reasonable assumptions, beliefs exhibit a pessimistic bias and, as a consequence, the risk premium is higher than in a standard setting.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rof/rfs004
ER  - 



